As the map shows, there are five ballot drop-off station in San Mateo County. Four of the stations are relatively close to one another where as the fifth one is relatively far away from the rest. A quick search using google confirms that the number and locations of the ballot drop-off stations are correctly shown on the map. Nonetheless, it is clear that only are small portion of land in San Mateo county is relatively “close” to the drop-off ballot stations. To better visualize the accessibility of ballot drop-off, five isochrones oof 10-min worth of walking distance are ploted below.

walk_10min <- mb_isochrone(
  SM_county_ballot,
  profile = "walking",
  time = 10
)

SM_county_ballot_walk_10min <-
  SM_county_ballot %>% 
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>% 
  cbind(walk_10min$geometry) %>% 
  st_as_sf()
leaflet() %>% 
  addMapboxTiles(
    style_id = "streets-v11",
    username = "mapbox"
  ) %>%
  addPolygons(
    data = SM_county_ballot_walk_10min,
    label = ~Name,
    color = "blue",
    weight = 2
  ) %>% 
  addPolygons(
    data = SM_county %>% 
      st_transform(4326),
    fill = F,
    weight = 2,
    color = "red"
  )

We can see that very only a very small part of San Mateo county is covered by those isochrones representing 10-min of walking distance to the voting ballot stops. If we are to define 10-min of walking distance as convenient access to ballot drop-off stations, then it is very clear that a very small subset of the total population are able to enjoy the convenience. Because voting is not as trivial as running errands, let us be more optimistic and assume that people would not be discouraged from voting just because they do not live within those isochrones. Instead, let’s use 20-min of cycling to draw new isochrones.

The logic behind the choosing of cycling in lieu of walking as pattern is that we hope to increase the size of isochrones to avoid including only a very small number of people, so as to reduce sensitivity to imputation errors and allows for equity analysis on different social groups. In terms of commuting profile, “cycling” instead of “driving” is used because cycling is a more realistic choice for non-drivers, which are more likely to be discouraged from dropping ballot in person. Especially during the ongoing Covid-19 public health crisis, non-drivers may prefer biking over other transportation means such as taking a taxi or riding a bus.

Compared to previous 10-min-walking isochrones, the 15-min-cycling isochrones are much largers, thereby covering a reasonable part of San Mateo county. Henceforth, the analysis of accessibility to ballot drop-off locations will be based on these 15-min-cycling isochrones.

SM_bgs <-block_groups("06", county = "081", year = 2017) %>%

SM_rac <-
  ca_rac %>% 
  filter(h_bg %in% SM_bgs$GEOID) %>% 
  left_join(
    SM_bgs, 
    by = c("h_bg" = "GEOID")
  ) %>% 
  st_as_sf()
SM_bg_isochrone_intersect <-
  SM_bgs %>% 
  st_intersection(
    SM_county_ballot_cycling_15min %>% 
      st_union() %>% 
      st_transform(26910)
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    leftover_area = st_area(.),
    perc_area = leftover_area / original_area
  )
SM_rac_ballot <- SM_rac %>% 
  left_join(
    SM_bg_isochrone_intersect %>% 
      select(h_bg = GEOID, perc_area) %>% 
      st_set_geometry(NULL)
  )

A quick review of the documentation for data structure reveals that varaibles CD01 ~ CD04 respectively represent number of jobs for workers with Educational Attainment: Less than high school; High school or equivalent,no college; Some college or Associate degree; Bachelor’s degree or advanced degree.

Because we have already tidied the data such that for each block groups the population in each educational attainment levels are estimated as: the total number of persons in each educational attainment levels times the percentage of areas covered by these 15-min-cycling isochrones. It is noteworthy that such methodology is essentially assuming a homogeneous distribution of different social groups (people of different socioeconomic status), i.e., population is randomly uniformly distributed. Such assumption could potentially limit the accuracy of our analysis in that filtering (where people of lower socioeconmics got filtered to poorer neighborhood with older buildings) does exist and that population is not uniformly distributed in space. Another factor that could potentially harm the usefulness of this analysis is that data on Educational Attainment is only available for workers of age 30 and older.

Other than Educational Attainment, socioeconomic status of interest typically include Income Level, as financial conditions usually dominates in many situations. For example, higher-income people have better access to private cars and could choose where they live (potentially close to ballot drop-off locations). The variable code CE01 to CE03 represent respectively number of jobs for workers with Income Level: jobs with earnings $1250/month or less; $1251/month to $3333/month; and greater than $3333/month.

Age also matters in that older people may find it necessary to have a ballot drop-off location close to where they live. The variable code CA01 to CA03 represent respectively number of jobs for workers with Age Category: age 29 or younger; age 30 to 54; and age 55 or older. The goal here is to sort of performs an equity analysis to see whether the accessibility to ballot drop off stations is differential between different social groups, the race is also of concern. CR01, CR02, CR03, CR04, CR05, CR07 respectively represent: number of jobs for workers with Race: White Alone; Black or African American Alone; American Indian or Alaska Native Alone; Asian Alone; Native Hawaiian or Other Pacific Islander Alone; Two or More Race Groups.

Overall, about 24% of the population are considered to be accessible to ballot drop-off locations, if we consider those living within those 15-min-cycling isochrones have easy access to voting. Several pie charts break down the 24% of voting-accessible population into different groups (educational attainment, income, age, race). From the plots, no significant inequality of ballot-drop-off-station accessibility is suggested. Among people of different educational attainments, people with Bachelor’s degree or advanced degree seems to be slightly favored, although the difference is almost negligible. Among three income groups, it seems people with monthly income greater than $3333 are slightly favored while the other two groups are disadvantaged. But again, these differences are quite minor. In terms of age, young people (age 29 or younger) seem to have slightly less accessibility to ballot-drop-off stations compared to other two groups of people. Last, when we look at the distribution of population within 15 min of cycling and compare that to the total population, we can find that Asisn alone tend to be slightly marginalized, whereas White alone are more or less favored in terms of accessible ballot-drop-off station. It should be noted that, however, the “population” we talked about here are based on number of works available, which means jobless people are not considered in this context. It is likely that results will change if those people are included.

Even though this analysis does not suggest any inequality in ballot-station accessibility, it is noted that the definition of accessibility could greatly affect our analysis. If the isochrones representing 10-min-walking distance were adopted, it is likely that the outcome of the equity analysis will change, e.g., some groups might be shown as the least accessible to ballot stations if we consider 10-min-walking distance to be the “accessible/bearable distance”. The choice of traveling mode “cycling”, could also be systematically disadvantaging certain groups not included in this analysis, e.g., people with physicak disabilities. Nonetheless, using 15min-cycling-isochrones in lieu of the 10min-walking-isochrones is a reasonable decision, considering that voting is not as insignificant as buying groceries and the fact that cycling is quite common in the Bay Area.
